## Research & Analysis Standards

### Citations
- Use authoritative sources: government sites, Statista, Gartner, Forrester, McKinsey, Deloitte, Mondaq
- Include URLs where available
- For customer quotes, cite participant anonymously (P1, P2, P3) with company name

### Participant Anonymization
- **Customer interviews:** Always anonymize participant names as P1, P2, P3, etc.
- **Preserve:** Company name and job title (e.g., "P1 - Senior Recruiter, Accenture")
- **Apply consistently:** Reports, slide decks, triangulation matrices, quotes, all documentation
- **Format examples:** "P1 (Accenture)", "P2 - HR Director, Baker Hughes", "P3 - Talent Acquisition Lead, Shell"

## Deck Generation

**Applies to**: All slide decks generated via Slide Deck MCP (`user-slide-deck-mcp`), including **110-slide-generator** (short decks) and **130-pmf-slide-generator** (full PMF roadmap decks).

**This section is the CANONICAL source** for slide typography, layout, and formatting. Individual deck generator rules (110, 130) reference these standards and add deck-specific logic only (e.g., PESTEL depth requirements, framework selection).

### Slide Content Guidelines
- Use British English spelling throughout
- **Maximum lines per slide**: Never exceed **7 rendered lines** of text per slide (8 lines ONLY for executive summary synthesis or unavoidable table complexity). **Rendered lines** = actual lines after text wrapping, not bullet count.
- **Character limits by bullet type** (prevents unpredictable overflow):
  - **Dense slides (PESTEL, Customer P1-P5, Recommendations)**: 180-240 characters per bullet (~2-3 lines rendered)
  - **Synthesis slides (Executive Summary)**: 200-250 characters per bullet (~2.5-3 lines rendered, max 4 bullets)
  - **Theme consolidation slides (Validated Themes)**: 140-180 characters per bullet (~1.5-2 lines rendered, max 2 themes per slide)
  - **SME slides**: 160-200 characters per bullet (~2 lines rendered, 7-8 total bullets including theme subheaders)
- **Calculation method**: `rendered_lines = bullet_count × avg_lines_per_bullet + subheaders + product_implication_lines`
- **Overflow indicators**: If any bullet exceeds character limit by >20%, or total rendered lines > 7, content MUST be split across 2 slides or moved to speaker notes.
- **Bullet length**: Keep individual bullets to 1-2 lines maximum. If a bullet wraps to a 3rd line, rewrite it to be more concise.
- Replace em-dashes with hyphens or commas
- Keep bullets concise; avoid run-on sentences
- Title case for slide titles
- Sentence case for bullet points
- Numbers: use commas for thousands (e.g., 9,922 not 9922)
- Percentages: 79% (no space before %)

### Typography Standards (Workday Slide Deck MCP)

**Canvas dimensions:**
- Canvas: 10.0in x 5.63in
- Title bar: Top ~1.2in (layout placeholder)
- Body content starts: `top_inches: 1.2`

**Font family:**
- All slides: "Archivo"
- Layout title placeholder: ~14pt bold (inherited from template)

**Body text font sizing by content density (VP AUDIENCE - LARGER TEXT REQUIRED):**
- **16pt**: Sparse slides (≤3 bullets, emphasis/key takeaway slides, 1/2 Headline content)
- **14pt**: **Standard slides (4-6 bullets) - Default for most content**
- **12pt**: Dense slides only (>6 bullets, comprehensive tables, PESTEL deep-dive with Product implication)

**In-slide subheadings:**
- **14pt bold** via run-level formatting in `paragraphs`
- Examples: Executive summary blocks, theme titles, section headers within body
- Supporting bullets inherit text box default size

**Section Title layout (divider slides):**
- Text box position: `left_inches: 3.3`, `top_inches: 1.5`, `width_inches: 5.6`, `height_inches: 2.2`
- **CRITICAL**: Do NOT use `paragraphs` array for Section Title slides. It triggers the auto-agenda extraction bug.
- Use a single `"text"` string with a newline (`\n`).
- Example: `"text": "S E C T I O N  0 1\nSection Name"`
- Apply formatting via text_box properties (`font_size_pt: 12`, `color: "ink"`) at the box level.

**Body text box (Title Only / Title Only_Alt layouts):**
- Standard dimensions: `left_inches: 0.7`, `top_inches: 1.2`, `width_inches: 8.6`, `height_inches: 2.8`
- Increase `height_inches` only for tables, charts, or unavoidably dense slides

### Density Validation Examples

These examples show how to calculate rendered lines and prevent overspill using character limits and bullet count caps.

**Example 1: PESTEL slide (Economic Factor) - COMPLIANT**

❌ **Before (Overspill - 15 rendered lines)**:
- 5 bullets × 3 lines each (300-400 chars per bullet) = 15 lines
- Product implication: 80 words = 4 lines
- **Total**: 19 lines → Text cut off at bottom ❌

✅ **After (Compliant - 7.5 rendered lines)**:
- 4 bullets × 2 lines each (180-220 chars per bullet) = 8 lines
- Product implication: 50 words = 2 lines
- **Total**: 10 lines → Use 12pt font for dense PESTEL = **7.5 rendered lines** ✅

**Revision technique**: Trim each bullet from 350 chars to 200 chars by consolidating related points into compound sentences with clear anchors. Example:
- Before (350 chars): "Industry reporting sizes India HR technology in the hundreds of millions USD with mid-single-digit to high-single-digit CAGR through the early 2030s across multiple analyst narratives from MarketsandMarkets and others. IMARC specifically cites India ATS market at approximately USD 0.30 billion in 2024 projecting toward USD 0.50 billion by 2033 at about 7.2 percent CAGR driven by AI adoption, cloud migration, mobile-first, and compliance automation themes"
- After (210 chars): "India ATS market sized at USD 0.30B (2024) toward USD 0.50B by 2033, 7.2% CAGR; AI, cloud, mobile, compliance automation drive growth (IMARC 2025). Industry syntheses cite hundreds of millions USD scale with mid-to-high single-digit growth toward 2030."

**Example 2: Executive Summary (Headline Outcomes) - COMPLIANT**

❌ **Before (Overspill - 11 rendered lines)**:
- 5 bullets × 2.2 lines each (200-280 chars per bullet) = 11 lines → Last bullet cut off ❌

✅ **After (Compliant - 10 lines, acceptable with 14pt font)**:
- 4 bullets × 2.5 lines each (200-230 chars per bullet) = 10 lines ✅ (acceptable for exec synthesis with rich context)

**Revision technique**: Reduce from 5 bullets to 4 bullets by consolidating related insights. Example:
- Before (2 separate bullets): "Triangulation is strong on identity, duplicates, and document UX; presales gap exports were not available" + "Priority direction: government-ID-aware dedupe with Legal minimisation, DPDP-aligned BGV consent"
- After (1 consolidated bullet, 223 chars): "Priority: government-ID-aware dedupe with legal minimization, DPDP-aligned BGV consent, hardened KYC gating, first-class BGC reinitiate, governed HiredScore activation—triangulation strong on identity and documents despite presales data gap."

**Example 3: Validated Themes - COMPLIANT (Split Across 2 Slides)**

❌ **Before (Overspill - 14 rendered lines on 1 slide)**:
- 3 theme subheaders = 1.5 lines
- 9 bullets × 1.8 lines each (140-160 chars) = 16.2 lines
- **Total**: 17.7 lines → Bottom content cut off ❌

✅ **After (Compliant - 7-8 lines per slide, split into 2 slides)**:

**Slide 1: Validated Themes 1-2**
- 2 subheaders + 6 bullets × 1.7 lines (140-160 chars each) = 1 + 10.2 = **11.2 lines** → Use **12pt font** = **8.4 lines** ✅

**Slide 2: Validated Theme 3**
- 1 subheader + 3 bullets × 1.7 lines (140-160 chars each) = 0.5 + 5.1 = **5.6 lines** ✅

**Revision technique**: Split 3 themes across 2 slides instead of cramming all on 1 slide. Maintain 3 bullets per theme structure. Use 12pt font when needed for density.

**Example 4: Customer Interview (P1) - COMPLIANT**

❌ **Before (Overspill - 11 rendered lines)**:
- 2 theme subheaders = 1 line
- 7 bullets × 2 lines each (180-220 chars) = 14 lines
- **Total**: 15 lines → Overspill ❌

✅ **After (Compliant - 8 lines with 12pt font)**:
- 2 theme subheaders = 1 line
- 5 bullets × 2 lines each (180-200 chars) = 10 lines
- **Total**: 11 lines → Use **12pt font** = **8.25 lines** ✅

**Revision technique**: Reduce from 7 bullets to 5 bullets by consolidating related insights, keeping character count to 180-200 per bullet for richness. Use 12pt font per 010-style-guide.mdc (>6 bullets threshold).

---

**Key Takeaway**: Rich bullet content (180-240 chars) + reduced bullet counts (4-5) + smart font sizing (12pt for >6 bullets) = v65-level density without overspill.

**Bullets - use `paragraphs` structure:**
- Prefer `text_boxes[].paragraphs` with `level: 1` for native PowerPoint bullets
- Avoid single `text` string with Unicode `•` characters
- Engine applies native bullets automatically when `level ≥ 1`

**Color palette:**
- Text colors: `ink` (dark navy, primary), `ballpoint`, `water_cooler`, `blue_sky`, `pencil`, `paper`, `laptop` (grey, de-emphasis), `staple`, `desk`
- **Always use `"ink"` for body text** - branded backgrounds are LIGHT, not dark

**Product Implication (PESTEL and similar slides):**
- Format: **12pt bold** + **yellow highlight** (`FFFF00`)
- Implementation: Use run-level formatting in `paragraphs`:
  ```json
  {
    "level": 0,
    "text": [
      {"text": "Product implication: ", "bold": true, "font_size_pt": 12, "highlight": "FFFF00"},
      {"text": "Implication text here.", "bold": true, "font_size_pt": 12, "highlight": "FFFF00"}
    ]
  }
  ```
- Start with "Product implication:" prefix
- 12pt retained for dense PESTEL context even when standard slides use 14pt

### Formatting
- Content position: Body text `top_inches: 1.2` (not 1.6) to avoid excess gap below title

### Speaker Notes (MANDATORY for content slides)
- Add `speaker_notes` to every content slide except: TITLE, Section Title, Bumper Slide
- Format: Bullet-pointed presenter guidance, then a "References:" section with live, working URLs
- Example:
```
"speaker_notes": "• Key point to emphasise.\n• Second talking point.\n\nReferences:\n• Source name: https://example.com/live-link"
```

**Detailed examples**: For Agenda slide patterns, Section Title anti-extraction patterns, Slide Title standards, and SWOT table structure, see `012-deck-generation-examples.md`.

